            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is the Parkland formula?</h2>
              <p>
                The Parkland formula is a widely used guideline for
                <strong>initial fluid resuscitation</strong> in patients with
                significant thermal burns. It estimates the volume of isotonic
                crystalloid (usually Lactated Ringer’s solution) required in the
                first 24 hours after injury.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Classic Parkland formula</p>
                <p>
                  $$\text{Total 24‑hour fluid (mL)} = 4 \times \text{weight
                  (kg)} \times \%\text{TBSA burned}$$
                </p>
                <ul class="mt-2">
                  <li>
                    Give <strong>50%</strong> of this volume in the
                    <strong>first 8 hours</strong> from the time of burn.
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    Give the remaining <strong>50%</strong> over the next
                    <strong>16 hours</strong>.
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <p>
                Only <strong>partial‑thickness (second‑degree)</strong> and
                <strong>full‑thickness (third‑degree)</strong> burns are counted
                in the %TBSA for the Parkland formula.
                <strong>Superficial (first‑degree)</strong> burns are excluded.
              </p>

              <h2>How this Parkland formula calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator is designed to be more practical than a simple
                formula by:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Accepting weight in <strong>kg or lb</strong> (with automatic
                  conversion).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Allowing you to choose the
                  <strong>Parkland factor</strong> (4, 3, 2 mL/kg/%TBSA or a
                  custom value).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Adjusting the first 8‑hour volume for
                  <strong>time since burn</strong> when fluids are started late.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Optionally adding a <strong>maintenance fluid rate</strong> on
                  top of resuscitation.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Providing <strong>infusion rates</strong> for the current
                  period and for hours 8–24.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Step‑by‑step example</h3>
              <p>
                Consider a 70‑kg adult with 30% TBSA partial‑thickness burns,
                presenting 2 hours after injury.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Enter weight = 70 kg, %TBSA = 30, factor = 4 mL/kg/%TBSA,
                  hours since burn = 2.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Total 24‑hour volume: $$4 \times 70 \times 30 = 8{,}400\
                  \text{mL}$$
                </li>
                <li>
                  First 8 hours (from burn): \(8{,}400 \times 0.5 = 4{,}200\)
                  mL.
                </li>
                <li>Next 16 hours: \(4{,}200\) mL.</li>
                <li>
                  At 2 hours post‑burn, there are \(8 - 2 = 6\) hours left in
                  the first 8‑hour window.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Suggested rate now: $$\text{Rate now} = \frac{4{,}200\
                  \text{mL}}{6\ \text{h}} \approx 700\ \text{mL/h}$$ (assuming
                  no fluids have been given yet; in practice, subtract any
                  volume already infused).
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Formulas used in this calculator</h2>

              <h3>1. Weight conversion</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>If weight is entered in pounds:</p>
                <p>
                  $$\text{Weight (kg)} = \frac{\text{Weight (lb)}}{2.20462}$$
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>2. Total 24‑hour fluid volume</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>$$V_{24} = F \times W_{kg} \times \%\text{TBSA}$$</p>
                <p class="mt-1 text-xs">
                  where \(F\) is the Parkland factor (mL/kg/%TBSA), \(W_{kg}\)
                  is weight in kilograms, and %TBSA is the percentage of body
                  surface area burned.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>3. Distribution over time</h3>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  $$V_{0-8} = 0.5 \times V_{24}$$ $$V_{8-24} = 0.5 \times
                  V_{24}$$
                </p>
                <p class="mt-1 text-xs">
                  \(V_{0-8}\) is the volume intended for the first 8 hours from
                  the time of injury; \(V_{8-24}\) is for the subsequent 16
                  hours.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>4. Adjustment for time since burn</h3>
              <p>
                Let \(t\) be the number of hours since the burn when fluids are
                started. The time remaining in the first 8‑hour window is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>$$t_{\text{left}} = \max(0,\ 8 - t)$$</p>
                <p>
                  $$V_{\text{remaining 0-8}} = \begin{cases} V_{0-8} & \text{if
                  } t \le 0 \\ V_{0-8} & \text{if no prior fluids assumed} \\
                  \text{(or } V_{0-8} - V_{\text{already given}}\text{ if
                  known)} \end{cases}$$
                </p>
                <p>
                  $$\text{Rate now} = \begin{cases} 0 & \text{if } t \ge 8 \\
                  \dfrac{V_{\text{remaining 0-8}}}{t_{\text{left}}} & \text{if }
                  0 \le t &lt; 8 \end{cases}$$
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>For hours 8–24, the baseline rate (without maintenance) is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>$$\text{Rate}_{8-24} = \dfrac{V_{8-24}}{16\ \text{h}}$$</p>
              </div>

              <h3>5. Adding maintenance fluids (optional)</h3>
              <p>
                If you enter a maintenance rate \(R_m\) (mL/hr), the calculator
                adds this to both the current rate and the 8–24‑hour rate:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  $$\text{Rate now (total)} = \text{Rate now (Parkland)} + R_m$$
                  $$\text{Rate}_{8-24,\ \text{total}} = \text{Rate}_{8-24} +
                  R_m$$
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Clinical considerations and limitations</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Guideline, not a prescription:</strong> The Parkland
                  formula is a starting estimate. Actual fluid needs vary.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Monitor urine output:</strong> Adjust infusion rate to
                  maintain appropriate urine output and hemodynamics.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Special populations:</strong> Children, elderly,
                  pregnant patients, and those with cardiac or renal disease may
                  require modified strategies.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Inhalation and electrical injuries:</strong> Often
                  need more aggressive resuscitation; consult burn specialists
                  and institutional protocols.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Avoid over‑resuscitation:</strong> Excess fluids can
                  lead to complications such as compartment syndromes and
                  pulmonary edema.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500">
                This calculator is for educational and decision‑support purposes
                only and does not replace clinical judgment, institutional
                guidelines, or specialist consultation.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>Do I include first‑degree burns in %TBSA?</h3>
              <p>
                No. Only partial‑ and full‑thickness burns are included in the
                %TBSA for the Parkland formula. Superficial erythema
                (sunburn‑like) is excluded.
              </p>

              <h3>What fluid should I use?</h3>
              <p>
                The classic Parkland formula uses
                <strong>Lactated Ringer’s solution</strong>. Normal saline is
                sometimes used but may increase the risk of hyperchloremic
                acidosis. Follow your local burn or critical care protocol.
              </p>

              <h3>How do I adjust if the patient already received fluids?</h3>
              <p>
                The strict Parkland approach subtracts any volume already given
                in the first 8 hours from the planned \(V_{0-8}\), and the
                remainder is infused over the remaining time. This calculator
                assumes no prior fluids unless you mentally adjust the remaining
                volume.
              </p>

              <h3>Is the Parkland formula used in children?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes, but children also require
                <strong>maintenance fluids</strong> and closer monitoring. Many
                pediatric burn protocols use Parkland (or modified factors) plus
                maintenance, and may rely on more detailed %TBSA charts
                (Lund–Browder).
              </p>
